review.reviewBody: Great short.... comfortable, like the front pockets ( they never look open ). I recommend. Sizing is perfect.
review.name: Nice short !!

review.reviewBody: I love these shorts! I should preface by saying, I am a female who likes longer shorts but not too long, and needs the bigger pockets. (shorts for females just don't have adequate pockets these days). These are the perfect length and hit just where I like them above the knee. The pockets are great, I love that the front ones are deep enough to hold my phone and other things like chapstick and keys. I like the zipper on the back right pocket, the only thing I would maybe change there is making those a little deeper to fit a phone better when you do want to zip it up. (I have an iPhone 13 and it's just tall enough that it doesn't zip). These shorts breath really well in the heat, dry quick when getting wet/splashed and are the perfect amount of stretch. I have now purchased a pair in almost every color. Would definitely recommend these shorts to anyone, male or female!
review.name: Great shorts!

review.reviewBody: I have worn these shorts now a few times, casually, and once mountain biking as I forgot my normal mountain bike shorts. The shorts have a great look and are functional in sport. My only grape is the metal zippers on the back can scratch furniture. I still would recommend the shorts.
review.name: Good look and functional form

review.reviewBody: These things fit great and the material is super nice and light. Waist is true to size and they sit a couple inches above my knees. These dry super fast and are pretty casual looking. They're very functional on the outdoor side of the house. Back pocket has a zipper to keep your treasures secured, and the pockets are mesh, making these pretty water friendly. Aside from functionality they still look good enough to grab a couple beers in. Highly recommend them and will probably be picking up a couple pairs. New go to shorts.
review.name: Super comfy and functional

review.reviewBody: These are my new favorite all-around shorts. Got my first pair last May, and used them for hiking and everyday use. They're lightweight, stretchy, and dry quickly. They are a bit more fitted but not too tight. I love the versatility.
review.name: Favorite Shorts!

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] nice breathable fabric. just needed a bit more beefy fabric for working in the field
review.name: yes

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] These shorts are great! They are lightweight which is exactly what i was looking for during the hot summer months in the south. At 5'l11 they sit just above the knee which is the style I wanted and the brick color looks great. So far Ive only worn them out casually but eventually ill get them out on a trail. That said, I have no reason to think they wont hold up as the build feels solid. Im quite happy with the purchase.
review.name: Great Feeling Casual Shorts

review.reviewBody: I've been using these shorts to hike in the Alps for a few months now and these are hands down my favorite shorts. The fit, cut, style, and comfort is perfect for everything from the trail to the city. The material is breathable, quick drying, and stretchy but still stylish.

review.reviewBody:
I used this for 2 weeks in Europe.

This is labeled as a 40L, yet I can fit so much more in my Cotopaxi 32L bag.  It's also a black hole and difficult to find anything in the bucket. I ended up having to unpack everything and repack it every two days. I like my items more organized than what this bag offers.  Also, the clips and some of the buckles are very cheap and flimsy.

What I really liked were the load lifters and the solid hip belt.  I have problems with lower back pain and this helped with that and it also kept a lot of weight off my shoulders.
review.name: It's okay, not worth the price.

review.reviewBody: I've only used this for one trip, but I'm already in love with it. It holds an absolute ton. I had two pairs of jeans, heavy sweatpants, a sweatshirt, and a pair of shoes, and there was still room for all my other stuff. I love that it opens like a suitcase. I love the interior and exterior cinch straps. The zippers and pulls seem very sturdy. It took me a minute to get the straps adjusted properly, but once I did, this was comfortable to wear. It fit in the overhead of the planes I was on. I love that it will sit upright on the floor when you put it down. I hope this pack lasts me many years.
review.name: A really solid pack for traveling

review.reviewBody: I spent 3 weeks in South America with this bag. It was perfect for all of the airlines! Lots of space, well built and good organization. I wish I could buy the 20L day back separately now but unfortunately you can only buy the 40+20L as a set.
review.name: Wonderful pack for carry on travel!

review.reviewBody: This is my personal travel bag.  The bag fits easily underneath of the seat in the plane. So, I could still have a carry on bag for longer trips.  Love the design.
review.name: Smart design backpack/duffle bag

review.reviewBody:
I bought this ~30 days ago and have used it on maybe 10 total runs thus far. At first I really liked it! Felt secure, good storage, accessible items.

But lately the elastic loops that go around the top of the water flasks have stretched out to the point they dont hold the flasks up anymore which makes it really annoying & difficult having to fish out a rubbery soft flask out of the holder mid-run. I havent tried anything else yet so not sure if this is unique to Salomon but definitely annoying.
review.name: Loved it initially - flasks dont stay up

review.reviewBody: The vest is a great choice! It holds a ton and comes with two water bottles which have been really useful on my long runs. Great product for anyone looking for a hydration vest!
review.name: Great choice!

review.reviewBody: I just ran a 50 miler with this vest it was light as a feather and kept me fueled all day!
review.name: This vest rocks!

review.reviewBody: I would give it a 3.5 of 5 starts. Love the no slosh bladders and overall snug fit and various pockets / compartments to carry things. Bladders hold enough fluid for about a 10m run. Vest is overall a great design and I would recommend it to others. Some improvements: sizing chart is off. I have a 40 chest. Per the dimension guidance (foto #2) I ordered a Medium. However, the actual vest is very tight causing the bladders to be way off to the side (foto #1) making them hard to reach when running - I need to take both hands and pull the bladder towards my mouth to drink. Secondly, its pretty hard to get the elastic string inside the clasp. The clasp mouth should either be slightly wider, or have more of an angled bevel to help guide the string to its mouth. It takes about 3-4 tries to get the string inside the claps. Again, I do like the vest, but think these corrections would help.
review.name: Nice product, some tweaks needed
comment: Hello, I appreciate you sharing your feedback with us. We constantly work to get better! Please keep in mind that your suggestions are being taken into consideration!

review.reviewBody: This vest fits well, and has good storage in a mix of locations.
review.name: Comfortable, good storage

review.reviewBody: This product was as advertised. It is comfortable and made of quality materials.  I have used it for a month and love it. Smartly designed packets and perfect for my long runs.
review.name: Great running pack

review.reviewBody: Bought this vest for running marathons and 50milers - Running my first marathon with it this weekend but I have had several 20+ runs in training with it and fits great! Nice and snug no bouncing around. The pockets are nice too! Plenty of space in the back as well.
review.name: Great Vest! Nice features

review.reviewBody: I was looking for a vest that's light, breathable and above all for my hydration needs. I've been in conditions wherein I've had no source of water to refill, so the 500ml flasks and an additional space to put in a bladder makes it huge! I've just done a couple of runs so far and I'm loving the fit so far. Plus, the red color looks great!
review.name: Quite literally, a second skin!

review.reviewBody: I've been skeptical of running vests forever, feeling suffocated by them. But not this vest!! It's so comfortable I hardly even feel it. It fits so much water and the back area is the perfect size for snacks, keys, a light jacket or another bladder. It has perfect pockets on the side for your phone or other items you'll need to access easily.
review.name: PERFECT RUNNING VEST

review.reviewBody: Fairly new convert to training with a hydration vest. Started with a cheap, different  brand one. Bought the Salomon as an upgrade. Chose a unisex one after reviews about  sides being too high. This one is totally unobtrusive, mesh sides and elastic front fastenings mean no annoying moving straps whilst running. position of pockets seem well thought out. Did find back a bit sweatiy after a long run though.
review.name: Pleased with purchase

name: Active Skin 8L Hydration Vest Set

review.reviewBody:
Got this shoe after having the previous generation (just titled Trailcross) for several years, which fit me as well as any shoe I've owned - snug but really comfortable with a half length, low profile arch support in them.

This shoe's design is terrible from a fit perspective: the fit is fine from the heel to the arch, where everything is relatively snug and form fitting, but after that things get pretty weird. The entire toe box feels like it's been shifted inwards a quarter inch on each shoe, meaning that the outside of my feet (specifically the outermost point of the 5th metatarsal) have a huge pressure point with the shoe while the inside of each foot has plenty of space. On top of that, the toe box is WAY bigger than it needs to be in terms of volume so my forefeet are swimming in these (I can almost lift the ball of my foot off the bottom of the shoe with the laces tied), which is the last thing you want during a rowdy downhill section.

I bought these without trying them on first (my fault) because I assumed they'd fit enough like the previous version to work fine and I liked the styling better, but this is a completely different shoe that is a big miss for me.
review.name: Weird Fit

review.reviewBody: After riding these tires for a while I can say they are pretty fantastic.   I have used them on technical trails both dry and wet.  They performed surprisingly well on wet damp muddy trails with lots of rocks and roots exposed.  Climbing on slick roots is not fun but these XC tires did a surprisingly good job.  A pair of these in 2.6 would be a hell of a fun tire!   These are not a mud tire or heavy duty downhill tire but they are great all around tire for a XC hard tail.
review.name: Follow Up Review

review.reviewBody:
aggressive for a drop bar gravel rig but i go through grass and fields and muck pretty routinely.  love how well they take me through it all.   700x2.1 had rubber hairs rub the fork so they likely need to go but only if i can find the 27.5x2.2s first.   not noticing the higher rolling resistance on pavement b/c i am too busy looking for places to jump onto dirt.  

set up required LBS to pop them onto rims to set as my little pump could not seat them.  once seated they filled nicely an easily though they still leak through side wall prolly b/c they're the race version.  but they air up before rides and keep topped off through rides just fine.   am refilling with air every 3 days and have also added a bit more sealant which seemed to help.   

these have transformed how and where i can ride.   i am in love, but know they're still a bit long in the tooth for the fork.   still, they look brilliant and ride extremely well.   may be seeking more Vittoria out for my bikes especially since Panaracer tires seem to have lost their stick over the years.
review.name: Gravel Bike Becomes Monster Cross
comment: looks great. running the same tire in 2.25 on a supercaliber and theyre amazing

review.reviewBody: I replaced the stock tires on my Trek when they wore out (500 miles).  So far the Barzo's seem like a great tire.  They mounted easily, I use tubes so I can not comment on a tubeless setup.   They far surpass the ride, grip and performance of the Bontrager XR2's I had.   I mostly ride my MTB in dry to semi moist conditions with an occasional mud hole and gravel trails thrown in.   I am not an extreme MTB or XC racer so I can not comment on their performance in that regard.   If you have a general use MTB that your looking for a good all around tire I think these are hard to beat.  If you ride your MTB on pavement mostly these are not the tire for you and if your a mud junkie or into technical downhill then you might be disappointed.
review.name: Great All Around Tire

review.itemreviewed: Vento Infinito Carbon 2 Wide Cycling Shoe
review.reviewBody: The search for a second pair of wide road shoes comes to an end. Always a fan of Fizik overall with their saddles over the years, trying their shoes made sense. Double BOA brings a ton of adjustment, the sole stiff were pretty much does not bent but the overall winner is the width! Currently my primary shoes are the Specialized Torch Sworks wide. Fantastic shoes extremely comfortable but they only come in black and they are in the mid 400 dollar range! The Fizik as comfortable, same level of adjustment, amazing color with yhe white and black and easy 100 dollars plus cheaper if you get them during a sale. On another note, interestly I sized down about half a size compared to my Specialized if that helps!
review.name: Super comfortable!

review.itemreviewed: Vento Infinito Carbon 2 Wide Cycling Shoe
review.reviewBody:
I was a long-time Sidi fanboy with 3 different pair in my closetbut unfortunately as I aged my feet started to grow wider and I did not like the Sidi Mega options.  So I did my research and eventually gave the Infinitos a try.  They.  Are.  Glorious.  

The toe box is very appropriately spaced, the soles are as stiff as any other high performance shoe Ive ridden, and the boa dials couldnt be easier to adjust on the fly.  I have also come to love the silicone grippers in the heel cup which do an outstanding job of keeping my foot firmly in place, even under the hardest of sprint efforts.  Additionally, the cleat placement is further back on the shoe, which has allowed me to achieve an even more appropriate bike fit and has mitigated some other foot and ankle issues related to having the cleats too far forward previously.

The one area in which these could use improvement is the tongue.  I was spoiled with the padding in Sidi and never had a hot spot no matter how hard I cinched down.  These, on the other hand, could stand for improvement in the tongue as they can pinch or create hot spots if you overshoot how aggressively you clamp down on the dials (or forget to loosen them back up after that mid-ride sprint).
review.name: Absolute Bangers

name: Vento Infinito Carbon 2 Wide Cycling Shoe

review.reviewBody: Brand new with extra sealant and 0 flats at Unbound on 40s.  Good grip in the mud sections as well.  Did not use any inserts.
review.name: No Flats at Unbound

review.reviewBody: I've ridden the 40mm for a while and they are very fast with great protection.  In the heavy snow and mud, they're bit slick, but rain/light mid, road and pack they do great.  If you want to go fast with protection, I'd highly recommend these.  I've done loads of large class gravel and mud, and got by just fine too, just takes a bit more effort.  On 25mm internal rims, they measured 42.5mm. On 22mm internal rims, they measured 41.5mm.
review.name: Perfect speed/puncture tire

review.reviewBody: Good grip, rolls fast, mounts easily, no air loss as a tubeless tire and no flats.
review.name: A fine tire

review.reviewBody: Got these tires  for my Fuji hybrid bicycle. like the low rolling resistance to near minimal. Grips  great on gravel. Overall a great handling tire that I would recommend.
review.name: Michelin's perfect blend of grip and low rolling resistance

review.reviewBody: Tried most of the top tier gravel tires, settled on these.  As a racer, puncture resistance is at the top of my list second is low rolling resistance. Other tires do this well but give up shock absorption of grip. The Power Gravels have great shock absorption and grip. The tradeoff is faster wear than some other gravel tires. For me, that's acceptable. I don't care how long a tire lasts if I'm constantly getting flats and crashing because of low grip. Raced BWR, Unbound and Crusher in the Tushar as well as weekly training rides on mine. Mostly hardpack or loose over hardpack. My theory as to why they ride and grip sop well is that the puncture belt is stretchy. That allows some suppleness. I've ridden other tires with good puncture resistance that rode like rocks unless you ran them with almost no air in them. My 40C Michelins are still supple at 32-34psi.
review.name: Best balance of attributes

review.reviewBody: As has been said here this is a decent tyre but frankly useless because it is near impossible to mount it even in the workshop with many tools .... on the road if a tube was needed, well, just ring the taxi and give up would be my advice. Shame but if you still want some, I have 2 brand new 35-622 available
review.name: A good tyre but Impossible to fit

review.reviewBody:
I had the 700x40 set-up tubeless on my Surly Cross Check and used them for everyday commuting, gravel riding, and bikepacking. I abused them on sharp rocks, singletrack, and rough road and they have held up great. These are definitely not a supple gravel tire, but good for people who want to prioritize durability. 

They are a pain to get the bead set and unset, maybe a little more so than other tires. The tight fit gave me a little more confidence in the tubeless set-up though and I never had any issues once they were on. 

Tread is good for a little bit of everything. I wouldn't say it really excels on any specific terrain, but holds it's own alright.
review.name: Bulletproof Tire

review.reviewBody: These were the most difficult difficult tyres to fit I have ever had. Mavic UST rims. It took nearly an hour and bent 4 parkside levers getting the last bit of tyre over the rim. Even getting one side on before inserting the tube required 3 tyre levers next to each other. Imagine trying to fit a car tyre by hand and you'll be close to the experience. There is literally no stretch in the bead, and they feel like they must be 10mm under sized to the rim. Such a shame because once they were on they proved to be fast and resilient to punctures but I cant go too remote incase I do get a puncture and am stranded unable to change the tube.
review.name: Near impossible to fit, but once on thankfully good puncture resistance

name: Power Gravel Tire - Tubeless

review.reviewBody:

But I love it - it is light and comfortable. The insulation is sufficient to keep you comfortable when you're very active and allows moisture to dissipate, keeping me drier than other jackets. The fabric has a bit of stretch in it and it has four outer pockets - two hand pockets and one on either side of the zipper on the chest. All in all, I think this is a great jacket for being active outdoors.

review.reviewBody: These are ski touring machines disguised as downhill boots.  They walk just as well as they ski, and they honestly do ski like downhill boots.  I struggled with getting a different pair of well-reputed touring boots to fit all season long and was about to throw in the towel until I came across the Zero G Tour Scout.  Can honestly say they have saved my season and allowed me to complete my dream trip (Bugs to Rogers Traverse).  The liners are somewhat thin but surprisingly really warm and comfortable.  Superb out-of-the-box fit - did not heat mold the liners or do any work on the shells, and skied some pretty big days at the end of this season with no blisters.  Lighter weight and better range of motion than some other leading touring boots this season too.  The only "flaw" I've been able to find is that the power strap doesn't stay in place when it is somewhat loosened, i.e. when in walk mode.
review.name: Perfect Touring Boot

review.reviewBody: Well, Im on year 29 with mine Yikes! Once I ask a cab driver in Mexico on a volcano climbing trip to stop at a gas station so we could get fuel That was 1995 I just used it for three days this week on the lakeshore trail into stehekin WA Thats 2024 Still works great!

review.reviewBody: This is an outstanding liquid fuel stove for year-round use. I use it primarily in winter and it rarely lets me down. Lightweight, robust, reliable, and simple to light are important features that matter to me. Thus far, I have only used it with white gas and cannot comment on its use with other fuels. The pump is easy to maintain as well. Since I use it in winter, I carry the Standard and Arctic pump on all remote trips. Depending on the temperature, I have to switch them regularly so it would be preferrable if one pump worked well in all temperatures.
review.name: Solid - Buy it!

review.reviewBody: I have used my the WhisperLite International for something like 20 years! From bicycle  camping  trips to Florida hurricanes  I used it for about three weeks straight when hurricane Charlie took out the power. About the only thing I have done to the stove is clean it maybe  every year or so and I think  the only problem I have had was I had to replace one little O-ring! That reminds me I have to replace the O-ring that I removed from the little service kit. I recommend that service kit I replaced that O-ring at night during a hurricane  power outage and all those O-Rings are special and your not going to find one when you roll into a campground at 02:00  AM in the rain  on your bicycle  and all you want to do is get something to eat and go to sleep  But if the stove needs an O-ring it is going to be cold Mountain House Chicken  Teriyaki  and a cold breakfast  So you need to get the service kit at least for peace of mind!
review.name: MSR WhisperLite International Stove!

review.reviewBody: This stove is solid! I bought it to replace my 30 year old WhisperLite stove. No more empty fuel canisters to try and recycle and the cost of fuel is much lower. Yes my original WhisperLite stove still operates fine, just went with a more modern design. I cold weather camp and you cant beat a white gas stove in the cold.

review.reviewBody: This is my favorite stove. I use in Africa every year to cook and sterile medical instruments. These stoves are the only stove that can be completly disassembled and cleaned in the field with min effort.

review.reviewBody: It packs up well, has done well up a few mountains so far. Should have bought the 32oz canister instead of the twenty. Has been reliable so far!

review.itemreviewed: Kento Pro High GTX Mountaineering Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: The sole is thick enough to ice climb. Extremely warm for the size. Comfortable and looks great. Absolutely 10/10. Most boots I wear a size 9 purchased a 9 and fits perfectly. Roomy toe box. Can't say a bad thing about this boot. This is a winter crampon/ snowshoeing boot you need for the mountains.
review.name: All in one

review.itemreviewed: Kento Pro High GTX Mountaineering Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I hv summitted one peak after I got my boots, about 10 miles and 3000 feet elevation gain. The boots are reliable and comfortable all through up and down the mountain. They are light weight.  I like them very much already!  It is about true to size. I usually wear 6.5, but thinking about thick socks for climbing, I ordered 7 instead. It is perfect.
review.name: Very comfortable

review.itemreviewed: Kento Pro High GTX Mountaineering Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: So comfortable right out of the box initially! However, once I started going up mountains it began a love/hate relationship, and I'm struggling with blistering on my heels while ascending.  Tried some different insoles, lacing techniques, and tape and am fairing much better.  I have used with hybrid crampons, and boots work well with them thanks to the crampon insert on the heel.  Boots are stupidly warm - I've worn them in single digit wind chills and my feet were warm and toasty.  I can't say these will be my "forever mountaineering boots," but they are doing well for my first pair.

review.itemreviewed: Kento Pro High GTX Mountaineering Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: Tested these on one of the Adirondacks High Peaks hike in cold and wet/slushy conditions. Spent 8 hours at a stretch and these amazing boots kept my feet warm and dry while being comfortable at the same time.

review.itemreviewed: Kento Pro High GTX Mountaineering Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: No break in needed, they did fit like a glove without hot spots or blisters on my first North Cascades climb wearing them (requiring a 12 mile approach, one way). Tested them in snow as well on some  day winter scrambles and my feet stayed completely dry and warm (as long as I was on the move). They fit crampons well and are sturdy for some front pointing on the most Cascades glacier climbs however I would consider a sturdier or double boot on ice climbs.
review.name: Great sturdy lightweight mountaineering boot

review.itemreviewed: Kento Pro High GTX Mountaineering Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: These boots are extremely supportive and comfortable, right out of the box. I bought 1/2 size bigger than my every day shoes and can fit a Sole insole and medium weight socks inside very comfortably. I have worn them about 10 times now and have not had any blisters or even a hot spot. Really impressed with these! **Update- I did a ton of winter hiking in these and they are still the best boots I have owned. They fit crampons well and the traction is excellent.
review.name: The best boots I've ever had

review.itemreviewed: Kento Pro High GTX Mountaineering Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I purchased these to use spring, summer and fall.  They are lightweight, comfortable right out of the box, and have a roomy toe-box.  I'm currently using training with a 38lb pack.  This is my first pair of boots from Mammut and I am pleased with my investment.
review.name: Comfortable, roomy toe-box, lightweight

name: Kento Pro High GTX Mountaineering Boot - Women's

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Have only taken this pack on one trek so far but it was great. Very comfortable and distributes weight nicely. I love how convient it is to access the inside of the pack with the front pouch. Only complaint is the water bottle pocket- its very difficult to get a 1.5 liter Nalgene in and out when the pack is full.
review.name: Have only taken this pack

review.reviewBody:
This pack is wonderful in most every aspect! I love the cross straps in the front and the added storage up front as well. The pack is also very comfortable. 

However, the only thing I'm not a fan of is how the day bag is assembled. There used to be snap clips to secure the day bag straps, now you have to loop it through & then weave it through the clip..this wouldn't be a big deal, however it is EXTREMELY hard to get it through. Having to assemble/disassemble it like this every single time is a pain & takes way more time than it should imo. It's also really hard to find a "how-to" online as i thought i was doing it wrong the first time because it was a struggle & taking way too long.

Other than this minor thing, the pack is great, and as per usual so is osprey - i just think they should steer back to the clips for the day pack. For now I am going to hand-sew my own on.
review.name: Great pack except for one thing....

Back country has pushed back on providing any sort of discount so now Im stuck w $50 shorts that I like but that have a stupid graphic I would never actually wear. Very poor QC and CX. Will be finding a new site to order my gear from, this is the last straw.

review.reviewBody: This is a comfortable bike seat. It is easy to attach to your bike and also adjusting the straps to the right size goes easy. The little basket on the backside is very handy to take a small plaid or rain jacket with you.
review.name: Good choice

review.reviewBody: Great quality product, super easy to install and transfer from my bike to my wifes. My daughter feels safe in it and I feel comfortable that its secured nicely to the bike. 10/10 recommend.
review.name: Great quality

review.reviewBody: The Dash RM is a nice, well-made rack mounted carrier. It is easy to install and remove. My main issue with the rack is the child harness, which is a major factor in a product like this. The shoulder straps do not have nearly enough adjustment and are very difficult to adjust. They also don't seem to properly tighten down on a child in the seat. I consistently lookback and see that the straps have fallen off around my child's shoulders. It is very disconcerting as this is a critical safety feature of the rack.
review.name: Great carrier, terrible harness.

review.reviewBody: Finally a child seat that fits my e-bike easy to install with no hassle.

review.name: Love it

review.name: I have a Lectric XP

review.reviewBody: I think the quality is acceptable, and found the installation clear cut. Storage is a non-issue for me as I always keep the seat mounted on the bike.
review.name: A++

review.reviewBody: Great seat for my 2 year old daughter. She fits well and the straps are easy to adjust. The foot straps help as well. On previous seat she would like to kick around. She doesn't mind her feet being strapped in and it works out great for me. Easy to fit onto rear rack and easy to remove. Worth the money.

review.reviewBody: The Coho is very well built! I'm happy with the quality. I wish when ordering, they gave the option for which tire to receive with the unit. But, whatever. Not a big deal. It pulls well, slightly noisy while using it. I notice the pannier bags are a bit low, so if riding roads close to curbs, it will rub. And burn a hole in the side or bottom. Also, at fast speeds like going down hills, it gets very sketchy when loaded! Their speed recommendation is encouraged! It will bounce you around a good bit. And make you feel unstable. I would recommend this product, with all that in mind! And, would buy again!
review.name: Recommend!

review.reviewBody: I used the trailer for packing in and out of a very remote area in Colorado. The trail was 24 wide max. It was canted down hill and very rocky. It was a horse trail. The only failure was the quick release holding the yoke. The securing nut vibrated off and was lost. I used a valve cap to secure it until I could get two nuts to replace the factory nut. I also used lock tight to hold it in place. I suggest a larger diameter rear wheel for more ground clearance. The trailer tracked very well and was really stable. It took a huge beating from the rocks but weathered it well. I also suggest adding rings to connect bungy cords. Connecting to the bottom rail on the trailer resulted in lost cords due to rocks pushing them off. The weight limit is about double what it should be When I had 40lbs in it made bike handling extremely difficult because the front end was light. Very happy with the durability and quality of construction.
review.name: 12 day Back country adventure.

review.reviewBody: These have been my daily shoes for the past couple of months and they're great! The upper is super breathable which makes it great for walking around town in the super months. The midsole has tons of cushion for long days on your feet. Lastly the outsole is grippy on just about every surface I've walked on! While there isn't much structure to the heel cup, I haven't had any issues with my heel slipping out. The tongue does tend to slide to the side of my foot throughout the day, but I haven't had any issues with the laces cutting into my foot. I would recommend staying with your regular shoe size when going with the Vasque Nows. My only dislike with this shoe is how much the heel sticks out. When I first got these I would occasionally catch it on stuff while walking around in tight places, but after a while wearing these I don't notice it too much.
review.name: Super comfortable daily shoe

review.reviewBody: I bought these about a month ago, to use as "every day" shoes during the tropical summer months. I have worn Vasque Breeze boots for several years and they are awesome! Here are some of the design issues with the RE:Connect Now; the tongue is too flimsy - it does not stay in place and the strings cut into the top of my foot. This is a minor issue and not a deal breaker. The extended and rolled heal is more of an issue. The extended heal gets in the way - I have to be careful walking down stairs, because the heal will grab the stair tread as I am lifting my foot up. Also, the rolled heal, creates an unnatural foot strike for me - certainly different than the Breeze. Lastly, for my weight the foot bead is too spongy and bouncy and the arch is too pronounced. The shoes are light weight and they breathe well, but not something I look forward to wearing much. I really wanted to like these shoes, but I think they could use some design changes or maybe I just need a different style of shoe.
review.name: Not what I was expecting

review.reviewBody: 5?8? and 175#. Wear 34x30 in most jeans/pants.  First thing I noticed was the drawstring was short, but it is attached in the back so it won?t pull all the way out. Added one of those black pinch adjusters like you would find on a hood, but bigger. Run both ends through and tie an overhand knot holding both. The additional bulk isn?t bad. Inseam feels like 31-32?. I would wash  these with my R1 pullovers to reduce pilling and not with regular pants/sweats.

review.reviewBody: I?m 5?10, 168lbs and the Medium fits me great. It?s not trim like a standard baselayer, but not super baggy either. I find most Patagonia pants are cut way too big. I was worried they would be too warm because I?m in NC, but they breathe quite nicely. I was disappointed to see how quickly the material pilled up, especially at this price. They are super comfortable, but are lacking a back pocket and zippers on the side pockets. Can?t say they?re perfect at this price, but they?re pretty good.

review.reviewBody: Paper thin color on the brown boots, so that the first scuff on the toe box shows raw light brown leather that is very hard to cover. As others have posted, no insoles of any type. Might be the first time that I have boots in the last 30 years that there was no insole. The volume is very large, allowing for full orthotics and heavy socks. Really too much volume for the size. On the plus side, no break in needed at all. The corollary to that is I cant imagine that these boots will hold up under any East Coast muddy rocky hiking. Sort of the urban equivalent of Zamberlains.
review.name: More show than go

review.reviewBody: The Danner Mountain Light Cascade Clovis GTX is indeed an iconic boot, but note this is old technology and other boot manufacturers deliver better out of the box comfort and more predictable sizing. If youre committed to buying these, this is what worked for me to dial in the fit. I sized down to 10.5 but normally wear an 11-11.5 in Asics and Mizunos and 45 European sizes and normally pair my boots with Smartwool medium weight boot socks. I broke them in without insoles (they do not come with insoles) and was told by the salesperson at the Danner store they are not designed to wear with insoles. However she suggested what worked for others are their proprietary half Airthotic Foam insoles ($18). After some break in (again w/o insoles ) the half insoles worked and significantly reduced heel sleeping. I also switched out the circle laces with the flat ones (comes with both pairs) allowing a more snug fit. If youre looking for a serious backpacking boot try other brands but these are without a doubt a very handsome boot.
review.name: What Ive learned getting the right fit

review.reviewBody: Break in is a must with these. Unlike fully synthetic boots, they will seem awkward to wear and use right out of the box. Give the materials some time to mold to your feet. It?s worth it. I added a small aftermarket insole, wore them around the house all day for about four days.
review.name: A bit awkward at first?.

review.reviewBody: I bought these because I wanted to re-live the experience when I had a similar pair in the 70's.  The style is timeless but the confort and construction have all the benefits that modern materials and craftsmanship can deliver.  I don't use them for hiking or anything technical, but rather to complete a more rugged look with jeans, a plaid shirt and a puffy down jacket.  I couldn't be happier.  The shoes fit like a glove and are VERY comfortable even on day one.  I suspect it will take several months to fully break them in and then they will be even more comfortable and stylish given normal wear and tear.  I am so glad that Danner still makes a boot like this!
review.name: 1970's Nostalgia but Better!

review.reviewBody: I tried the Mountain Light and the MLII. This was a narrower boot, not as chunky. Fits true to size. Breaking in is a commitment, but worth it. Get on youtube and search on how to best tie a hiking boot so it does not loosen or slip. If you do that you wont get blisters. I did at first but figured it out after. I ordered metal tipped laces and they are a nice addition with a surgeon's knot. These are a great addition to my gear.
review.name: Very pleased

review.reviewBody: I received my Mountain Light Cascades. This makes my 5th pair of Danners. The new boots are the quality I expect from Danner,  BUT where are the airthotic inserts that came with the previous 4 Danners I purchased? Am I required to purchase the inserts separately? I have an extra pair of inserts I can use till this matter is resolved. The boots are Danners which makes them the best.  The fit is the same as my other pair of Mountain Lights. I wear a 10.5. I purchased a 10 and the fit is good. Backcountry provided fast shipping with excellent communication.
review.name: Grade of A-.

review.reviewBody: I've been climbing in Miuras LU for the past few years and decided to change things up recently. After reading the reviews I ordered these in full size larger than Miuras and they fit like a glove! Sticky rubber, moderate curve + overall comfort, these shoes will take you on an adventure. For reference, my running shoes are 7.5/38, my Miura's were 37.5, Vapors are 38.5.
review.name: <3 these shoes!

review.reviewBody:
I got these shoes after reading some of the reviews here and I do love them. They are one of the best fitting shoes I?ve found for my semi wide asymmetrical foot. Be aware they do run a bit smaller than other models. In the instincts I am around a 41/41.5 and in these I am a 42. If you have instincts, I?d order these at least a half size larger than those. 

As others have mentioned, I?d consider these a moderate/flat shoe. They pretty much immediately lose their downturn after the first time you climb in them. I don?t mind that because I actually prefer flatter shoes, and it makes them pretty good for slab. However the one downside to this is for whatever reason, the stiffness doesn?t really seem to last in the soles. After just a couple months there is barely any support in the sole. Recently on a relatively short Multipitch with hanging belays my feet were absolutely killing me after just a couple pitches. That being said, they are still a great allrounder, but if you?re wanting these for longer climbs I?d look elsewhere. They edge really well, and the xs edge rubber provides a nice balance of stickiness and durability. I mainly use these on granite climbs ranging from slab to vertical, and for that purpose they are wonderful. I like them enough and they fit my foot perfectly that I?ve bought a second pair but I?m considering exploring other options now just because of the sole stiffness durability.
review.name: Great moderate shoe, with one downside

review.reviewBody: I normally wear size 39.5 in La Sportivas.  Bought the Scarpa Vapors in size 40.  They are more like size 38 in La Sportivas.  Here is a comparison pic with my TC Pros (39.5).   Can't give you a review on its performance since I can't even get into them.
review.name: Way Too Small

review.reviewBody: These shoes are decent but not my favorite. Theyre suitable for easy trad which is mostly what I bought them for, but on climbs with small foot placements I found that the rubber under my big toe was folding, though my feet might just not have the right shape for these. (Bought online without trying on) I wear a 42.5 La Sportiva and got these in 45 and they have a similar tightness. Also, the slight downturn was completely gone after 1 use :(
review.name: Decent but not Amazing

review.reviewBody: This shoe is a marvel of modern misengineering. It's mid sole and toe appear to have been modeled to fit a club-flippered walrus. Paired with a flimsy elastic heel, one cannot walk 3 steps without their foot coming dislodged - even if you buy a half-size down as I had. Utter garbage. I will only grace Teva the relief of accepting my return if they also commit to planting a forest to offset the ecological disaster of this shoe line.
review.name: Absolute trash shoe

review.reviewBody: I thought this shoe was completely neutral when I purchased it and it showed up with a bright green ribbon on top and bright green insole. Not as pictured. I do love these shoes and have several pairs but I expect it to be as shown. I usually order a 9 even though I'm a 9.5 because they look better and are more comfortable sized down.
review.name: Colors weren't as shown

review.reviewBody: I've bought 2 pairs of these shoes in the less than a year, and here's why. They are great...to begin with. But with just a short time, the heel of the sole starts to peel off of the bottom. My first pair did it in less than 2 months, and my 2nd pair lasted maybe 3 months before it started happening. And I am not rough on my shoes by any means. I work a simple cashier job and I make sure I'm using my hands to take them off rather than using my other foot. Absolutely ridiculous for the price of these that the sole starts to peel off so quickly. It's very disappointing too because I absolutely LOVE these shoes otherwise. They have been the only thing I can find that don't cause me pain in my back and feet.
review.name: Great shoes with 1 HUGE FLAW

review.reviewBody: Thess shoes fit really nicely on my feet. However I wouldn't say they're Slip-Resistant. Nearly slipped on the floor a couple of times with these shoes. Better as walking shoes than hiking.
review.name: Fits good

review.reviewBody: ReEMBER is a comfy slipper that you can wear outside the house. The unisex sizing is OK as long as you don't have narrow feet (mine are 2 different sizes due to surgery so I have to size to the larger foot). In boots I wear a women's size 11 but size 10 works for me without socks.
review.name: great all around slipper

review.reviewBody: I've bought Teva product in the past and have been very satisfied, hence buying this product, however I'm very disappointed due to the heel cover constantly rides down, having to stop and pull it back up. They are very comfortable until you start walking in them and have to stop and pull the heel flap/covers up. They fit perfect, just don't perform.
review.name: I would not buy this product again

review.reviewBody: Shoes are very snug and have not stretched too much in the past couple months of use.  I don't wear them for long periods.  I do a couple routes and take them off to give my feet a rest.  They grip indoor walls really well and seem to be pretty durable.  I would recommend this shoe to other climbers.
review.name: Great shoes

review.reviewBody: Overall great grip on the climbing wall for gym bouldering. Lots of versatility, solid intermediate level shoe. The toe box can be a little steep and uncomfortable but it does slightly stretch, then fits like a glove.

Everyone says wide feet but I dont think they actually have wide feet. I am a 6e width 43. The shaman doesnt even come close. Awesome shoe but if you actually have wide feet on a brannock, youre not just some bouldering kid who thinks he has wide feet, look elsewhere. These might just be roomy for average feet.
review.name: Lets talk about wide

review.reviewBody: I have wide feet and this is one of the only performance shoes I've felt "comfortable" in.
I love these shoes

Got the Shamans over 3 months ago and I love them. Don't have too big experience in climbing shoes as this is only my second pair but after using Kronos in the beginning, this is a definite step up in terms of possibilities on the wall.
I'm climbing in the gym only so far and they work perfectly fine no matter if we're talking about pushing from the small edges or smearing on hi-angle volumes - I haven't yet found a scenario in which these shoes would limit my ability of completing the climb. Edging, toe- or heel hooking, smearing, everything seems to work just as it should in Shamans.
I'm wearing size 8.5 US with my street size being 9 US and after a bit painful break in period they fit my foot perfectly and are super comfortable without any loose spots inside.
The overall quality is great, the only thing i'm slightly worried about are the velcro straps that look like the weakest spot of the shoe - they already show some signs of usage and small fraying, but I'm using them pretty intensively and so far there's no serious damage to them. I've also used the front part of the rubber way faster than expected but I'm pretty sure that's due to my sloppy footwork.
Overall, the Shamans feel so good for me that I don't think I'm looking for another model anymore, I plan to resole them as long as possible and probably just buy another pair when the first one is too worn out.
review.name: Perfect all-around shoe

review.reviewBody:
These are the first all-around shoes in my climbing journey. I am very lucky because it suits me very well after a short break-in period. I have an Egyptian foot shape with narrow to medium width and it is very comfortable for me like the second skin. Shamans are not stiff and not soft, they have a great combination of sensitivity and precision with performance. Good toe hooking and heel hooking ability as well as grabbing and smearing (love bump is a small obstacle here but for my 83kg it is not a problem to smear it).

Long story short, great all-arounders who can help to progress with different routes and angles in any discipline.  One more thing is the edging ability, it is good, not perfect but you need experience and strength in your toe for that.

Highly recommend.
review.name: Great all-rounders!

review.reviewBody: This is my second pair and I only worry that they will be unavailable in the future. I have a lot of foot problems and these keep me running and working out.
review.name: Most comfortable and grippy shoes ever!

review.reviewBody: Astrals have always been my go-to for river days, and they also make a fantastic travel shoe! However, the comfort and fit of the 2.0 pales in comparison to the older version. I will be holding on to my older pair as long as humanly possible because I can barely tolerate a full day in the 2.0s. The new versions are MUCH narrower and less comfortable, especially when sockless. Folks with narrow feet, I cannot recommend these shoes enough! Folks that used to enjoy the roominess of the older Brewess, look elsewhere. (The Loyaks are little less structured, so can still work well for us!)
review.name: No longer a good fit for wide feet

review.reviewBody: I love these shoes. They are comfortable to wear and dry quickly after being in the water. They are also super cute.
review.name: Super cute and comfy

review.reviewBody: Great water sport shoes.  Comfortable and soles that grip rocks like they are stuck there
review.name: Astrals are the best

review.reviewBody: These are the best shoes Ive ownedand I should know, since this is my fifth pair! Theyre sturdy and flexible, fit great for my narrow feet, and keep on keeping on for mile after mile.
review.name: Perfect shoe

review.reviewBody:
So far so great: grippy natural rubber siped soles, roomy wide toe box that doesnt pinch, lightweight canvas construction that doesnt get waterlogged like most sneakers & should dry fairly quickly, good midsole for padding when bouncing around on sailboat decks with lots of metal fittings. Lovely light blue color that is essentially a neutral & goes with everything I own. My only question left is how long will the soles last before going hard? If it is longer than a year that these will hands-down beat the Big Brand boat shoes. And the 11 is sized roomy enough to fit Rocky Socks and wool socks inside, meaning I dont need to haul around seaboots for most coastal sailing.

10/10 I love them so far!
review.name: Great for sailing!

review.reviewBody:
Im In love with these shoes!
If water is involved Im where them!
review.name: Great shoes

review.reviewBody: Love these. Simply love them. Super comfortable, perfect fit, no break in needed. My first pair and definitely not my last.
review.name: Footwear that ensures you wander comfortably

review.reviewBody: These offer great grip, excellent support, and easy on and off. Being out on the water in the ocean with  all kinds of conditions, including needle-like rocks, my feet feel secure. They take a bit of care to get sugar sand off, and a bit of time to dry, but its worth it for the foot protection.
review.name: Tested for toughness and grip in the Bahamas

review.reviewBody: My last pair of Brewess, I bought in 2015, I put them through the wringer and they finally the bit the bullet this year so I purchased a new pair. I really like the updated version. Super comfy and a more durable seeming than the originals. I've done some creek scrambling and whitewater kayaking in them and so far so good. I've always guided in Astrals, I prefer the full foot coverage that keeps you from stubbing your toes on rocks and they drain sand and water easily. Will forever be my go to water shoe.
review.name: My go to!

This boots were ordered with high expectations. I have purchased and worn KEEN hiking shoes and boots for years and had very good experience with quality of construction, fit and comfort.

review.itemreviewed: Circadia Polar Mid Hiking Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody:
[This review was collected as part of a promotion.] My feet were scanned as
US 7.1 2E
EU 39.2 3E
UK 6.5 G
- so pretty wide. In the winter months I get a bunion flare up on my right foot and I walk around in misery. After going through some other brands and the wrong sizes I got these in 7.5 and they fit great. Truly warm and spacious. A true winter boot to protect my feet. I tested them on a 8 mile hike in 8 inches of snow and some stream crossings and my feet stayed warm and dry. 
My only ding is they are a little clunky in overall size and the cushioning is a little harder than I'd like. It took a little adjusting to walk in these. Overall a solid purchase :)

I marked these as run wide. For me this is good thing. They fit my 2E feet so not a problem that these aren't offered in an official wide size like the non polar version of this boot.
review.name: Solid Boot - Very warm and waterproof

review.reviewBody: I recently started wearing some SUGOi Evolution bib shorts that I am a fan of, so I thought I'd check our their jersey selection as well.  I really liked this mountain design and decided to pick it up in both Medium and Large to see how their jerseys fit.  In my other go-to brand (PI) I am a M in their more relaxed jerseys and a L in their more semi-fit jerseys.  For this jersey the M is a bit more snug than I'd prefer (but not terrible)- and the L is far too long for me, being a shorter rider.  I'd say if there were a half-size between M and L that would be perfect for me.  But, there isn't-- so I kept the Medium.  I'm told the ZAP technology *is* very reflective and noticeable, which is great.  The sleeves on this jersey are a big longer than I'm used to, but not terrible.  They fit snug, but not restrictive.  One complaint is that the jersey material seems to snag easily.  I've thrown my gloves in my back pockets of my PI jerseys... well, almost every single time I finish a ride... and I've never once had my PI jerseys snag from the velcro.  On my first ride doing this, I noticed some snags of the jersey material inside the pocket that held the gloves.  A bit disappointing, but something I'll be aware of and will have to be more careful that the gloves are fully closed before throwing them in my back pocket.  Anyway, pretty nice jersey, decent quality, good design, little pricey... will probably pick up another style or two as I need to add more jerseys to my collection.
review.name: Bit long, snags easily, but visible!

I can pull the elastic tight on the long pant, which is generously in length, but it still pools/poofs at the bottom and is just not as convenient as the ankle pant. Good quality and fit, I just don't think I will wear it as much for my purposes as the ankle pant. I wear a small in most pants but size-down in the Dynama pants. However, the waist seam design is not as stretchy as other parts so your hip proportions will determine whether this will be true-to-size or you need to size-down.

review.reviewBody: Not sure how I feel about these yet. I love how lite they are! I have used them on two trips so far. I had a couple trips where they jammed up in the ice and were very difficulty to screw in. Intermittently while screwing into the ice this would happen. However, there were two other climbs with different ice conditions and whether where they performed just as well as my other screws. Not sure why this is, maybe it has to do with weather/ice conditions. Not sure yet, still experimenting with them.
The light weight is great! I do find the screws slightly harder to place than the express screws.

Great screw!
Crazy light, good for most types of ice. 
Havent had any issues with them binding up in wetter ice, but have heard of it happening. 
Highly recommend, but wouldnt climb with just these, would have several steel screws as well.
review.name: Ultralight ice screws

review.reviewBody: Bought these for a now canceled trip to Denali.  They have quick bite and screw in for the initial few mm. The ice we were testing them in caused them to turn easy and then stop like you were screwing into dirt or rock. They werent it was the aluminum and moisture in the ice causing problems. We had regular BD screws also and they didnt have the issue. In all a great screw and you cant beat the weight.
review.name: Super Light but Weird to Screw In

review.reviewBody:
I posted a review after first getting a couple of these last season, and have since replaced most of my steel screws with these. I've used other brands aluminum screws, and BD have the best feel. The wire gate extension feels more durable and solid that other "express handles" and the extra leverage makes them easy to place quickly. definitely an improvement from the steel screw express handle. 
A few reviews have talked about them getting stuck. This seems to be an issue with aluminum generally rather than these specifically, and I have had the same issues with competitors screws. I do find that in really wet ice they will freeze in place more readily than steel screws, and feel almost like they bottomed out. with a good twist to break the resistance they will usually drive the rest f the way as normal. The longer screws provide meaningful weight savings. For V-threads the larger bore is somewhat helpful, and the green anodization makes seeing the screw path in the ice easier than steel screws. Finally, since these have a larger diameter than almost anything else on the market (petzl UL is slightly larger), the ability to rebore holes is nice, especially in areas that get Swiss-cheesed every weekend. as more people use UL screws this advantage will diminish.
review.name: Best on the Market

review.reviewBody: I've used the express screws for the past 5 years to anchor my spearfishing darkhouse. One of the best investments I've made in spearing equipment...anchor screws into the ice very quickly...like screwing into butter!
review.name: Outstanding

review.reviewBody: With dry ice these are great.  Quick to bite, easy to drill.  However in any ice that is wet or has a lot of moisture in it, they will almost certainly have issues getting placed.  In wet ice they will often become literally stuck and you cannot place them fully without really hammering on the hanger.  I know aluminum screws always have more friction, but these are noticeable worse than my petzl aluminum screws.  I'll take the weight of steel screws, at least they can be fully placed in all ice conditions.
review.name: Good at times, terrible at others

review.reviewBody: Ordered a few of these about a month ago. Awesome screws. Light weight, bite quickly, lever is snappy and feels solid. They don't go into wet ice as well as steel screws, but that's pretty normal for aluminum screws. No complaints!
review.name: Awesome Screws!

review.reviewBody: Super lightweight, sharp right off the shelf & knob spins great. I've heard about the screws not being placed & removed easily, I did notice some resistance but nothing beyond normal while leading ice
review.name: Drill baby drill

review.reviewBody:
I bought these screws a couple of weeks ago and got to try them.  They are amazingly light. The handle is great, it has a spring action to come back to its rest place.  The teeth are aggressive and dig very fast in the ice. It is almost unbelievable how quickly the screw holds in place.

But...for some reason after a few turns, or even midway into insertion, the screw just gets stuck.  It halts a bit less suddenly than if you were to hit rock. But it is quite stuck. It takes a lot of force to get it to turn again, to the point that I sometimes think the handle could break.  Sometimes I was not able to get it unstuck using the knob, I had to wrap my hand around the screw plate and really put a lot of force to get it moving again.  Sometimes it happened 2 or 3 times during the placement of a single screw.  In the same ice I placed BD Express screws without any such problem. 

I am not sure why this is happening. My guess is the type of material allows the water to refreeze on it easily. And the large diameter of the screw (largest I have seen so far) means more surface the ice can grab on.
review.name: Gets stuck mid-way
comment: Thank you for your review. This is not something I have experienced or heard of with our Ultralight Ice Screws. If you'd like us to take a closer look I'd recommend that you file a warranty claim with us here: https://warranty.bdel.com/CreateCase/StepOne In any case thank you again for your review.

review.reviewBody:
Perfect hiking pants (and probably so many other applications). Jogger silhouette but the tiniest bit less slim than joggers of yesteryear  and it makes them perfectly mobile but still looking good. Happy to do away with needing a belt to hold up my pants bc that buckle just gets awkward with my backpack waist strap anyhow. I am pretty skinny, 28 in waist and no hips, and smalls fit but felt the tiniest bit loose in the waist  they would stay up I think but voila(!) a good drawstring for security. The pockets actually hold your phone and a wallet too.

The ferrosi material is amazing. These slay the Pata terrebone joggers - I have both and these are stretchier and more breathable and yet more sturdy and it shows why ferrosi-based jackets and pants have won awards for years.

I am to use this backpack until it can no more. It's perfect!

I'm 5'4 tall, 50kg heavy and this pack got me through a 90 mile (7 day) hike without shoulder pain. It's got straps on the shoulders that'd bring the backpack closer to my back, no packs I ever had before had this, and I had never been so comfortable. That being said, it could get tighter, but I am simply very small.

Despite its lightness, this thing is strong. I stuffed all I could in the elastics, capacity of 28litres is probably an understatement and the main was also full to the brims. After this first hike, partner is now buying his first RAB backpack for our next one, next month :)

review.reviewBody: I have used a lot of different packs over the years, and this has to be the best thought through pack I have come across. It has all the little features that you need, like the shoulder strap and hip pockets, the unique should strap approach, pulling tha pack into your back, and the three mesh pockets for overspill/quick access to kit. I used it recently for a walk down the French and Spanish coast, and it never let me down, day after day. So comfortable, and able to cope with all the asks made of it. Defintely recommend.

review.reviewBody: Overall I'm very happy with my aeon ultra 28, it swallows my lightweight 2 season sleeping bag, thermarest neo air X lite, durston X mid 2p solid, walking poles, insulated jacket, pillow, spare base layers/hooded fleece , cook set etc with plenty of room for water carrying etc. The inner pocket is ideal for a small first aid/emergency kit. I bought the Rab soft flask which is very comfortable compared to a hard bottle in the right hand chest harness pocket. The only gripe I have (hence the 4 stars) is the sternum strap attachment clips....they are constantly sliding up and unclipping themselves, slapping me in the chest or stomach. The lower strap in particular suffers with this problem, please Rab...remedy this problem. I have added a webbing daisy chain on the inner edge of the chest harness straps so I can attach my custom omm chest pack, if Rab included these they could use a more secure attachment system similar to what Montane use, which would also make it easier for the user to repair in the field as opposed to the sliding rail system. If Rab sort this problem, I'll give the pack 5 stars.

review.reviewBody:
I'm really enjoying this pack. I used to use a running rucksack from another well-known running brand but was looking for something exactly like this - a simple chest rig on the front for essentials, good hip pockets, and a simple back compartment that can hold a decent amount of kit. This has it all. 

I use it for running home from work when it can carry a laptop, my clothes and shoes easily. It's also perfect for days out in the countryside. It's also perfect for those with children. Mine is usually filled with water bottles, snacks, gloves, hats, all conveniently stashed in the super stretchy side and back pockets - these for me were one of the key draws to this rucksack - loads of space for all those things you just need to quickly stuff somewhere and avoid the faff of constantly opening your main compartment, plus, it keeps the wet stuff outside and the stuff inside dry!

It has a nice sleek design, even with the stuff pockets in use, and just looks smart, so it's been suitable for taking to and from work and things aren't flapping around all over the place. 

The chest rig is good, and very versatile. 

My only comment would be that as smaller man, with a 36" chest and 29" waist, this doesn't do up as tight as I'd like. When it's laden down, it's actually fine, but when it's quite empty, it's fine walking, but doesn't quite feel as snug as I'd like when running.
review.name: Really loving this as my new everyday rucksack, runcommute pack and general outdoors daysack / overnight bag

review.reviewBody: They fit my feet very well; even my orthotist likes them and thinks they are perfect for my feet. I would have given 5 stars, but the Altra Customer Service never answered my emails.

review.reviewBody: My picture speaks for itself. My first Olympus has 150 miles on it and still look strong. Just bought 2 more pairs
review.name: Love it

review.reviewBody: Comfortable, stable, and fell apart within 300 miles. It is a very stable shoe with great grip. No blisters in my time with them. I found them to be comfortable on moderately long days (26 miles). They started showing wear on the upper material within the first hundred miles. After finishing 125 miles yesterday in the Wind River High Route, both sides of both shoes were blown out, the heel cups look like they had an ice cream scoop taken out of the padding, and the midsole had compressed where I could feel the rocks more than I would like. It is an excellent show but the lack of durability is disappointing considering the premium price.
review.name: Durability issues for hiking

review.reviewBody: I've had every iteration of the Olympus. They are my go-to standard for long trail runs! I appreciate that Altra has kept the wide toe box in the Olympus. The Olympus 5 has some issues with the sole peeling up, but it seems to have been resolved in the 6! Love these shoes! Happy trails to you!
review.name: Again and again!

review.reviewBody: These have been my standard trail shoes for yrs and I love them. However I'm now on my 3rd pair and the sole on the forefoot has peeled away from each pair. I've returned them & replaced them and it is not a fluke.
review.name: Great shoe...one flaw!

review.reviewBody: I run long distances. Bought half size larger and these run small so overall fit is ok. Laces were way too short, can't even tie the shoe. Build quality is below average. It sounds like I am pumping up an air mattress with one shoe constantly when running on dirt road after any water crossing. Tread is coming off. Maybe have 350 miles on them. 1 star due to disappointment in overall performance. That being said I will buy another pair when they discontinue them and they are on sale.

review.reviewBody: It's a great shoe no doubt..but the left one has developed this annoyingly loud squeaking noise every step I take. Would I buy another pair? Definitely. The comfort of the shoes while running is great. Other than the annoying squeaking noise awesome shoes
review.name: I would buy this product again and again but..

review.reviewBody: I was not sure if I would like the thick cushioning after the LP, but these worked out well. My complaint is that after 1 year of light use the side wall of the shoe is failing and sole separating.
